This is not a “Yay, go me for fixing it” thread. Pillows are basic patient care. It shouldn’t be this hard 6/6.

Two pillows acquired after signing my life away and promising them my first born. 

Trek three floors back to the ward in a different wing

Pillows put in pillowcases and delivered to the patient. He’s much happier and still doesn’t want a block 5/

Medirest: Go to the linen store in the basement.

(NB No mention of a form or a code). I trek to the basement. 

Linen store man: You need a form and a 6 digit code. 

He gives me the form. I call the ward clerk and she gives me a code 4/

Me: Where do I find a pillow?

Nurse: “In the linen room”. 

The linen room is empty of pillows. 

Nurse: “Ring Medirest” 3/

I went to see a lovely nonagenarian who might need a block for analgesia for rib fractures. His biggest concern at the moment isn’t his ribs, but that he doesn’t have a pillow. I start an epic journey to find a pillow 2/

NHS pillows. A 🧵.

One would think a ward bed comes with a pillow, right? However, pillows in the NHS are a scarce commodity and, often, rarer than hen’s teeth. 1/
